# Frontend .env example
#
# IMPORTANT — READ BEFORE USING:
#
# Anything in a frontend .env file (or referenced by config.js) is PUBLIC.
# It will be visible to anyone who views the site source. There is no way
# to truly hide values that the browser needs to read.
#
# DO NOT put secrets here:
#   - Discord bot token
#   - Discord client secret
#   - PayPal client secret / webhook secret
#   - Database credentials
#   - Stripe secret keys
#   - Any API key with write permissions
#
# Keep all secrets on your backend only. The backend should perform
# privileged actions (PayPal capture, Discord OAuth token exchange, etc.)
# and expose only the result to the frontend over a normal API call.
#
# Variables below are safe to expose because they're meant to be public.
# They are NOT read by this site automatically — this file only documents
# what you might use if you wire up a real backend later.

PUBLIC_INVITE_URL=
PUBLIC_SUPPORT_DISCORD=
PUBLIC_SUBSCRIBE_URL=
PUBLIC_DASHBOARD_LOGIN_URL=
PUBLIC_CONTACT_EMAIL=
